[src:polars/apache-arrow] Arrow can be used with Apache Parquet, Apache Spark, NumPy, PySpark, pandas and other data processing libraries.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] The project includes native software libraries written in C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, MATLAB, Python (PyArrow), R, Ruby, and Rust.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] Arrow allows for zero-copy reads and fast data access and interchange without serialization overhead between these languages and systems.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] Arrow has been used in diverse domains, including analytics, genomics, and cloud computing.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] Apache Parquet and Apache ORC are popular examples of on-disk columnar data formats.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] Arrow is designed as a complement to these formats for processing data in-memory.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] The hardware resource engineering trade-offs for in-memory processing vary from those associated with on-disk storage.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing data between the two formats.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] Apache Arrow was announced by The Apache Software Foundation on February 17, 2016, with development led by a coalition of developers from other open source data analytics projects.
[src:polars/apache-arrow] The initial codebase and Java library was seeded by code from Apache Drill.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:polars/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] Polars is a blazingly fast DataFrame library for manipulating structured data.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] The core is written in Rust, and available for Python, R and NodeJS.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] A DataFrame is a 2-dimensional data structure that is useful for data manipulation and analysis.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] With labeled axes for rows and columns, each column can contain different data types, making complex data operations such as merging and aggregation much easier.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] Due to their flexibility and intuitive way of storing and working with data, DataFrames have become increasingly popular in modern data analytics and engineering.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] Polars is written in Rust which gives it C/C++ performance and allows it to fully control performance-critical parts in a query engine.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] A more extensive introduction can be found in the next chapter.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] Polars has a very active community with frequent releases (approximately weekly).
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] We appreciate all contributions, from reporting bugs to implementing new features.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] Read our contributing guide to learn more.
[src:polars/docs-pola-rs] This project is licensed under the terms of the MIT license.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In programming language theory, **lazy evaluation**, or **call-by-need**, is an evaluation strategy which delays the evaluation of an expression until its value is needed (non-strict evaluation) and which avoids repeated evaluations (by the use of sharing).
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is often combined with memoization, as described in Jon Bentley's *Writing Efficient Programs*.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] If so, the stored result is simply returned.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] If not, the function is evaluated, and another entry is added to the lookup table for reuse.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is difficult to combine with imperative features such as exception handling and input/output, because the order of operations becomes indeterminate.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The opposite of lazy evaluation is eager evaluation, sometimes known as strict evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Eager evaluation is the evaluation strategy employed in most programming languages.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation was introduced for lambda calculus by Christopher Wadsworth.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] For programming languages, it was independently introduced by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation is used particularly in functional programming languages.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] When using delayed evaluation, an expression is not evaluated as soon as it gets bound to a variable, but when the evaluator is forced to produce the expression's value.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is fundamental in big data frameworks such as Apache Spark, where computations on distributed datasets are delayed until results are explicitly needed, allowing for execution optimizations and reduction of unnecessary processing.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation allows control structures to be defined normally, and not as primitives or compile-time techniques.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] These have the usual semantics, i.e., `ifThenElse a b c` evaluates (a), then if and only if (a) evaluates to true does it evaluate (b), otherwise it evaluates (c).
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] That is, exactly one of (b) or (c) will be evaluated.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Similarly, for `EasilyComputed || LotsOfWork`, if the easy part gives **True** the lots of work expression could be avoided.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Finally, when evaluating `SafeToTry && Expression`, if *SafeToTry* is **false** there will be no attempt at evaluating the *Expression*.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Conversely, in an eager language the above definition for `ifThenElse a b c` would evaluate (a), (b), and (c) regardless of the value of (a).
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This is not the desired behavior, as (b) or (c) may have side effects, take a long time to compute, or throw errors.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] It is usually possible to introduce user-defined lazy control structures in eager languages as functions, though they may depart from the language's syntax for eager evaluation: Often the involved code bodies need to be wrapped in a function value, so that they are executed only when called.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation has the advantage of being able to create calculable infinite lists without infinite loops or size matters interfering in computation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The actual values are only computed when needed.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] For example, one could create a function that creates an infinite list (often called a *stream*) of Fibonacci numbers.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The calculation of the *n*-th Fibonacci number would be merely the extraction of that element from the infinite list, forcing the evaluation of only the first n members of the list.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In the function numberFromInfiniteList, the value of infinity is an infinite range, but until an actual value (or more specifically, a specific value at a certain index) is needed, the list is not evaluated, and even then, it is only evaluated as needed (i.e., only to the desired index).
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Provided the programmer is careful, the program completes normally.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell syntax, "`:`" prepends an element to a list, `tail` returns a list without its first element, and `zipWith` uses a specified function (in this case addition) to combine corresponding elements of two lists to produce a third.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In computer windowing systems, the painting of information to the screen is driven by *expose events* which drive the display code at the last possible moment.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] By doing this, windowing systems avoid computing unnecessary display content updates.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Another example of laziness in modern computer systems is copy-on-write page allocation or demand paging, where memory is allocated only when a value stored in that memory is changed.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Laziness can be useful for high performance scenarios.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] An example is the Unix mmap function, which provides *demand driven* loading of pages from disk, so that only those pages actually touched are loaded into memory, and unneeded memory is not allocated.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] MATLAB implements *copy on edit*, where arrays which are copied have their actual memory storage replicated only when their content is changed, possibly leading to an *out of memory* error when updating an element afterwards instead of during the copy operation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The number of beta reductions to reduce a lambda term with call-by-need is not larger than the number needed by call-by-value or call-by-name reduction.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Call-by-need embodies two optimizations - never repeat work (similar to call-by-value), and never perform unnecessary work (similar to call-by-name).
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also lead to reduction in memory footprint, since values are created when needed.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In practice, lazy evaluation may cause significant performance issues compared to eager evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] For example, on modern computer architectures, delaying a computation and performing it later is slower than performing it immediately .
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This can be alleviated through strictness analysis.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also introduce memory leaks due to unevaluated expressions.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Some programming languages delay evaluation of expressions by default, and some others provide functions or special syntax to delay evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In KRC, Miranda, and Haskell, evaluation of function arguments is delayed by default.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In many other languages, evaluation can be delayed by explicitly suspending the computation using special syntax (as with Scheme's "`delay`" and "`force`" and OCaml's "`lazy`" and "`Lazy.force`") or, more generally, by wrapping the expression in a thunk.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In lazy programming languages such as Haskell, although the default is to evaluate expressions only when they are demanded, it is possible in some cases to make code more eager—or conversely, to make it more lazy again after it has been made more eager.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This can be done by explicitly coding something which forces evaluation (which may make the code more eager) or avoiding such code (which may make the code more lazy).
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] *Strict* evaluation usually implies eagerness, but they are technically different concepts.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] However, there is an optimisation implemented in some compilers called strictness analysis, which, in some cases, allows the compiler to infer that a value will always be used.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In such cases, this may render the programmer's choice of whether to force that particular value or not, irrelevant, because strictness analysis will force strict evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell, marking constructor fields strict means that their values will always be demanded immediately.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The `seq` function can also be used to demand a value immediately and then pass it on, which is useful if a constructor field should generally be lazy.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] However, neither of these techniques implements *recursive* strictness—for that, a function called `deepSeq` was invented.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Also, pattern matching in Haskell 98 is strict by default, so the `~` qualifier has to be used to make it lazy.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In C++, the `std::ranges` library uses lazy range adaptors.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In Java, lazy evaluation can be done by using objects that have a method to evaluate them when the value is needed.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The body of this method must contain the code required to perform this evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Since the introduction of lambda expressions in Java SE8, Java has supported a compact notation for this.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The `Lazy` interface with its `eval()` method is equivalent to the `Supplier` interface with its `get()` method in the `java.util.function` library.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Each class that implements the `Lazy` interface must provide an `eval` method, and instances of the class may carry whatever values the method needs to accomplish lazy evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In the above, the variable a initially refers to a lazy integer object created by the lambda expression `() -> 1`.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Evaluating this lambda expression is similar to constructing a new instance of an anonymous class that implements `Lazy<Integer>` with an eval method returning 1.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Each iteration of the loop links a to a new object created by evaluating the lambda expression inside the loop.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Each of these objects holds a reference to another lazy object, b, and has an eval method that calls `b.eval()` twice and returns the sum.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The variable b is needed here to meet Java's requirement that variables referenced from within a lambda expression be effectively final.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This is an inefficient program because this implementation of lazy integers does not memoize the result of previous calls to eval.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] It also involves considerable autoboxing and unboxing.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] What may not be obvious is that, at the end of the loop, the program has constructed a linked list of 11 objects and that all of the actual additions involved in computing the result are done in response to the call to `a.eval()` on the final line of code.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This call recursively traverses the list to perform the necessary additions.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This allows the previous example to be rewritten to be far more efficient.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] Java's lambda expressions are just syntactic sugar.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In JavaScript, lazy evaluation can be simulated by using a generator.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] You can run this example yourself by going to the Kotlin Playground.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] To verify that the program lazily loaded `isThePizzaReady` instead of initializing it beforehand as true we need to check the output of the program.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] As we can see when the program reads from `isThePizzaReady` it prints out a statement we put inside the lazy code block on line 4.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The statement on line 4 does not execute more than once.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x the `range()` function computes a list of integers.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In Python 3.x the `range()` function returns a generator which computes elements of the list on demand.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] This change to lazy evaluation saves execution time for large ranges which may never be fully referenced and memory usage for large ranges where only one or a few elements are needed at any time.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x is possible to use a function called `xrange()` which returns an object that generates the numbers in the range on demand.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The advantage of `xrange` is that generated object will always take the same amount of memory.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] From version 2.2 forward, Python manifests lazy evaluation by implementing iterators (lazy sequences) unlike tuple or list sequences.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] , the first element '0' is printed when need arises.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In the .NET framework, it is possible to do lazy evaluation using the class `System.Lazy<T>`.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] The class can be easily exploited in F# using the `lazy` keyword, while the `force` method will force the evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] There are also specialized collections like `Microsoft.FSharp.Collections.Seq` that provide built-in support for lazy evaluation.
[src:polars/lazy-evaluation] In C# and VB.NET, the class `System.Lazy<T>` is directly used.
[src:polars/pandas-software] The development of Pandas introduced into Python many comparable features of working with DataFrames that were established in the R programming language.
[src:polars/pandas-software] The library is built upon another library, NumPy.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Developer Wes McKinney started working on Pandas in 2008 while at AQR Capital Management out of the need for a high performance, flexible tool to perform quantitative analysis on financial data.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Before leaving AQR, he was able to convince management to allow him to open source the library in 2009.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Another AQR employee, Chang She, joined the effort in 2012 as the second major contributor to the library.
[src:polars/pandas-software] In 2015, Pandas signed on as a fiscally sponsored project of NumFOCUS, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit charity in the United States.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Pandas is built around data structures called *Series* and *DataFrames*.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Data for these collections can be imported from various file formats such as comma-separated values, JSON, Parquet, SQL database tables or queries, and Microsoft Excel.
[src:polars/pandas-software] A *Series* is a one-dimensional array-like object that stores a sequence of values together with an associated set of labels, called an index.
[src:polars/pandas-software] It is built on top of NumPy's array and affords many similar functionalities, but instead of using implicit integer positions, a Series allows explicit index labels of many data types.
[src:polars/pandas-software] A Series can be created from Python lists, dictionaries, or NumPy arrays.
[src:polars/pandas-software] If no index is provided, pandas automatically assigns a default integer index ranging from 0 to n-1, where n is the number of items in the Series.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Series can be used arithmetically, as in the statement `series_3 = series_1 + series_2`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] This will align data points with corresponding index values in `series_1` and `series_2` (similar to a join in relational algebra), then add them together to produce new values in `series_3`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] A Series has various attributes, such as `name` (Series name), `dtype` (data type of values), `shape` (number of rows), `values`, and `index`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] They can be used in many of the same operations as NumPy arrays, with additional methods for reindexing, label-based selection, and handling missing data.
[src:polars/pandas-software] A *DataFrame* is a two-dimensional, tabular data structure with labeled rows and columns.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Each column is stored internally as a Series and may hold a different data type (numeric, string, boolean, etc.).
[src:polars/pandas-software] To retrieve a DataFrame column as a Series, use either 1) the index (dict-like notation) or 2) the name of column if the name is a valid Python identifier (attribute-like access).
[src:polars/pandas-software] DataFrames support operations such as column assignment, row and column deletion, label-based indexing with `loc`, position-based indexing with `iloc`, reshaping, grouping, and joining.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Merge operations implement a subset of relational algebra and allow one-to-one, many-to-one, and many-to-many joins.
[src:polars/pandas-software] pandas' syntax for mapping index values to relevant data is the same syntax Python uses to map dictionary keys to values.
[src:polars/pandas-software] For example, if `s` is a Series, `s['a']` will return the data point at index `a`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Unlike dictionary keys, index values are not guaranteed to be unique.
[src:polars/pandas-software] If a Series uses the index value `a` for multiple data points, then `s['a']` will instead return a new Series containing all matching values.
[src:polars/pandas-software] A DataFrame's column names are stored and implemented identically to an index.
[src:polars/pandas-software] As such, a DataFrame can be thought of as having two indices: one column-based and one row-based.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Because column names are stored as an index, these are not required to be unique.
[src:polars/pandas-software] If `data` is a Series, then `data['a']` returns all values with the index value of `a`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] However, if `data` is a DataFrame, then `data['a']` returns all values in the column(s) named `a`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] To avoid this ambiguity, Pandas supports the syntax `data.loc['a']` as an alternative way to filter using the index.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Pandas also supports the syntax `data.iloc[n]`, which always takes an integer *n* and returns the *nth* value, counting from 0.
[src:polars/pandas-software] This allows a user to act as though the index is an array-like sequence of integers, regardless of how it is actually defined.
[src:polars/pandas-software] pandas also supports hierarchical indices with multiple values per data point through the "MultiIndex" class.
[src:polars/pandas-software] MultiIndex objects allow a single DataFrame to represent multiple dimensions, similar to a pivot table in Microsoft Excel, where each level can optionally carry its own unique name.
[src:polars/pandas-software] In practice, data with more than 2 dimensions is often represented using DataFrames with hierarchical indices, instead of the higher-dimension *Panel* and *Panel4D* data structures.
[src:polars/pandas-software] pandas supports a variety of indexing and subsetting techniques, allowing data to be selected by label, index, or Boolean conditions.
[src:polars/pandas-software] For example, `df[df['col1'] > 5]` will return all rows in the DataFrame `df` for which the value of the column `col1` exceeds 5.
[src:polars/pandas-software] The library also implements grouping operations based on the split-apply-combine approach, enabling users to aggregate, transform, or restructure data according to column values or functions applied to index labels.
[src:polars/pandas-software] For example, `df['col1'].groupby(df['col2'])` groups the data in 'col1' by their values in 'col2', while `df.groupby(lambda i: i % 2)` groups all data in the whole DataFrame by whether their index is even.
[src:polars/pandas-software] The library also provides extensive tools for transforming, filtering and summarizing data.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Users may apply arbitrary functions to Series and DataFrames, and because the library is built on top of Numpy, most NumPy functions can be applied directly to pandas objects as well.
[src:polars/pandas-software] The library also includes built-in operations for arithmetic operations, string processing, and descriptive statistics such as mean, median, and standard deviation.
[src:polars/pandas-software] These built-in functions are designed to handle missing data, usually represented by the floating-point value NaN.
[src:polars/pandas-software] In addition, pandas includes tools for reorganizing data into different structural formats, with methods that can reshape tabular data between "wide" and "long" formats and pivot values based on column labels. pandas also implements a flexible set of relational operations for combining datasets.
[src:polars/pandas-software] For instance, `merge()` links row in DataFrames based on one or more shared keys or indices, supporting one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships in a manner analogous to join operations in relational databases like SQL.
[src:polars/pandas-software] DataFrames can also be concatenated or stacked together along an axis through the `concat()` method, and overlapping data can be further spliced together using `combine_first()` to fill in missing values.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Furthermore, the library includes specialized support for working with time-series data.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Features include the ability to interpolate values and filter using a range of timestamps, such as `data['1/1/2023':'2/2/2023']` , which will return all dates between January 1 and February 2.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Missing values in time-series data are represented by a dedicated NaT (Not a Timestamp) object, instead of the NaN value it uses elsewhere.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Pandas has been criticized for its inefficiency.
[src:polars/pandas-software] The entire dataset must be loaded in RAM, and the library does not optimize query plans or support parallel computing across multiple cores.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Wes McKinney, the creator of Pandas, has recommended Apache Arrow as an alternative to address these performance concerns and other limitations.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Otherwise, he says, "my rule of thumb for pandas is that you should have 5 to 10 times as much RAM as the size of your dataset".
[src:polars/pandas-software] Sort foods by calories (descending order):df.sort_values("calories", ascending=False) Note: Any missing values are automatically sorted to the end of the Series.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Group items by category and calculate average macros:df.groupby("category")[["carb_g", "fat_g", "protein_g"]].mean() This returns a GroupBy object that is analogous to a collection of DataFrames.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Find the highest-calorie food per category:df.loc[df.groupby("category")["protein_g"].idxmax()] `idxmax()` returns the index value of the maximum value.
[src:polars/pandas-software] `idxmin()` performs an analogous function with the minimum value.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Handle missing data:df.loc[2, "fiber_g"] = None # Simulate a missing value df["fiber_g"].fillna(df["fiber_g"].mean()) This replaces the `None` value with `NaN`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Alternatively, we can also drop rows containing missing values by calling `df.dropna()`.
[src:polars/pandas-software] To merge datasets with different key column names, use the parameters `left_on` and `right_on` instead.
[src:polars/pandas-software] Categorize food by calories:df["calorie_level"] = pd.cut( df["calories"], bins=[0,100,200,300], labels=["Low", "Medium", "High"] ) This splits numeric data into separate "bins" or intervals, thereby allowing continuous measurements to be analyzed as discrete categories.
[src:polars/polars-software] As of September 2025, Polars has over 24 million monthly downloads and over 250 million downloads in total.
[src:polars/polars-software] The initial code commit was on June 23, 2020.
[src:polars/polars-software] Polars started as a "pet project" by Ritchie Vink, who was motivated by the limitations of the software tool pandas that is used to organize and work with data.
[src:polars/polars-software] Vink aimed to address those limitations with a data processing library written in the Rust programming language.
[src:polars/polars-software] Ritchie Vink and Chiel Peters co-founded a company of the same name to develop Polars, after working together at the company Xomnia for five years.
[src:polars/polars-software] In 2023, Vink and Peters successfully closed a seed round of approximately $4 million, which was led by Bain Capital Ventures.
[src:polars/polars-software] In September 2025, Vink and Peters raised €18,000,000 (about US$21,000,000) in a Series A round led by Accel, along with Bain Capital Partners and angel investors.
[src:polars/polars-software] Vink and Peters have also developed other services like Polars Cloud and Polars Distributed that are built around Polars.
[src:polars/polars-software] The core object in Polars is the DataFrame, similar to other data processing software libraries.
[src:polars/polars-software] Contexts and expressions are important concepts to Polars' syntax.
[src:polars/polars-software] A context is the specific environment in which an expression is evaluated.
[src:polars/polars-software] Meanwhile, an expression refers to computations or transformations that are performed on data columns.
[src:polars/polars-software] Polars was also designed to be "intuitive and [have] concise syntax for data processing tasks".
[src:polars/polars-software] Given that Polars was designed to work on a single machine, this prompts many comparisons with the similar data manipulation software, pandas.
[src:polars/polars-software] One big advantage that Polars has over pandas is performance, where Polars is 5 to 10 times faster than pandas on similar tasks.
[src:polars/polars-software] Additionally, pandas requires around 5 to 10 times as much RAM as the size of the dataset, which compares to the 2 to 4 times needed for Polars.
[src:polars/polars-software] These performance increases may be due to Polars being written in Rust and supporting parallel operations.
[src:polars/polars-software] Polars is also designed to use lazy evaluation (where a query optimizer will use the most efficient evaluation after looking at all steps) compared with pandas using eager evaluation (where steps are performed immediately).
[src:polars/polars-software] Some research on comparing pandas and Polars completing data analysis tasks show that Polars is more memory-efficient than pandas, where "Polars consumes 63% of the energy needed by pandas on the TPC-H benchmark and uses eight times less energy than pandas on synthetic data".
[src:polars/polars-software] Polars does not have an index for the DataFrame object, which contrasts pandas' use of an index.
[src:polars/polars-software] Polars and pandas have similar syntax for reading in data using a `read_csv()` method, but have different syntax for calculating a rolling mean.
[src:polars/polars-software] Dask is a Python package for applying parallel computation using NumPy, pandas, and scikit-learn, and is used for datasets that are larger than what can fit in memory.
[src:polars/polars-software] Polars is for single-machine use, while Dask is more for distributed computing.
[src:polars/polars-software] DuckDB is an in-process SQL OLAP database system for efficient analytical queries on structured data.
[src:polars/polars-software] Both DuckDB and Polars offer excellent analytical performance, but DuckDB is more SQL-centric for running queries, while Polars is Python-centric.
[src:polars/polars-software] Apache Spark has a Python API, PySpark, for distributed big data processing.
[src:polars/polars-software] Similar to Dask, Spark is focused on distributed computing, while Polars is for single-machine use.
[src:polars/polars-software] So Polars has an advantage when processing data on a single machine, while Spark may be preferred for larger datasets that don't fit on a single machine.
